Void Linux Documentation - OS_Wiki

System Name: Void Linux
Kernel: Linux (monolithic kernel)
Based on: Independent
Created by: Juan Romero Pardines
Maintained by: Void Linux community
Initial release: 2008
Source model: Open source
License: Mainly GPL and other free software licenses
Architecture support: x86_64, i686, ARM (aarch64, armv7)
Package manager: XBPS (X Binary Package System)
Desktop Environment: Any (CLI installation; commonly used with XFCE, LXQt, MATE, Cinnamon, or others)
System type: Desktop / Server / Workstation
Target audience: Advanced users, Linux enthusiasts, rolling-release users, DIY system builders
Not recommended for: Beginners without Linux experience, users seeking plug-and-play desktop with preinstalled software
Official site: https://voidlinux.org
ISO size for download: ~700 MB – 1.5 GB (depending on edition and desktop)
Minimum requirements:
- CPU: x86_64-compatible processor
- RAM: 256 MB minimum (1 GB recommended for GUI)
- Storage: 2 GB minimum for base system (more for desktop environment and applications)
- Boot: BIOS or UEFI supported
- Network: Internet connection recommended for installation and updates

Description: Void Linux is an independent, rolling-release Linux distribution designed for experienced users who want full control over their system. It uses the XBPS package manager and can be installed from minimal command-line ISOs, allowing users to build a fully customized operating system. Void Linux offers various desktop environments but does not include a default DE. Its rolling-release model ensures that software stays up to date while maintaining system stability.
